{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":30170,"record_hash":"sha256:4f23285321de4951f7c6b866640119085305f39512d0392a7cf0d76679d88778","timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:34:35.101Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Created [agentlog-sync-lifecycle.md]([REDACTED:entropy].md:1) and linked it from [README.md]([REDACTED:entropy].md:62).\n\nThe design note proposes `but agentlog sync [--remote <name>]` as an explicit exchange command that:\n\n- fetches/materializes remote agentlog metadata\n- serializes local agentlog metadata\n- pushes it back with bounded non-fast-forward retry handling\n- stays scoped to agentlog keys only\n- keeps capture/hook local-only\n\nThe big design point is that current GitMeta high-level APIs are close, but direct `Session::serialize()` / `pull()` / `push_once()` would exchange all shareable metadata. The note recommends a small GitMeta API extension for destination/key-scoped sync rather than mutating persistent filter rules or reimplementing transport in `but-agentlog`.\n\nThe main open question I’d want your taste on soon: should the dedicated destination be named simply `agentlog`, or something more GitButler-specific like `gitbutler-agentlog`?","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T16:34:35.101Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}